## Key Architecture Decisions

Decided during Mar 27, 2026 planning session:

### Tags

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| Inject tag definitions + usage counts into extraction prompt (Phase 0) | LLM only sees names today → vague tags. Definitions + counts = smarter choices. |
| `pin:` dimension with 3 levels (critical/important/reference) | User needs explicit control. "Pin that" → prompted for level. Never decay. |
| `permanent:true` tag for infrastructure facts | Some facts never change. Quarterly manual review to confirm. |
| No date tags on every memory | `created_at`/`updated_at` timestamps already exist. Tags are for semantics, timestamps are for temporal ordering. |
| Normalize existing tags before adding new features | Fix inconsistencies first so analysis is clean. |

### Scoring & Recall

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| Azure scoring profile: 80-day freshness, 2.0x boost | Startup context shifts fast. Recent memories should rank higher. 80 days keeps last month's architecture decisions visible. |
| Content 1.5x weight, tags 1.2x weight | Content matters most, tags are secondary signal. |
| Importance field 2.0x boost | High-importance always ranks well regardless of age. Pin overrides importance (critical=10, important=9, reference=8). |

### Lifecycle

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| Increment `access_count` on every recall | Free usage data. Currently in schema but never used. |
| 90 days + 0 accesses → soft delete | Strong signal memory isn't useful. Soft delete = recoverable. |
| `permanent:true` and `pin:*` exempt from decay | User-protected facts should never auto-delete. |
| Quarterly manual review of permanent memories | Prevents "permanent" from meaning "forever unquestioned." |

### Quality Evaluation

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| Claude Sonnet as judge (not GPT-5.2) | Independent model family = no self-grading bias. GPT-5.2 extracted the facts; Claude judges them. |
| 6-dimension rubric (tag accuracy, specificity, anchors, fact accuracy, atomicity, ClawBot utility) | Comprehensive but weighted. ClawBot utility uses SOUL.md + USER.md for persona-grounded scoring. |
| Score ALL ~100 memories, not a sample | Claude-as-judge has no per-call cost. Full coverage eliminates sampling error. |
| Missed-fact analysis from session transcripts | Catches extraction gaps, not just tag quality. |
| Existing `_score_extraction_quality()` analyzed separately | It's GPT-5.2 self-scoring. Understand it, but don't use as primary judge. |

### Dual-Target

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| Same codebase, `--target` flag | Both systems use identical SQLite + Azure AI Search architecture. Config differs, code doesn't. |
| ClawBot first, Claude Code second | ClawBot has the richer memory set and more complex needs. Prove the system there first. |
| Claude Code gets tuned rubric (5 dimensions, no ClawBot utility) | No SOUL.md/USER.md on Mac. Replace with "code relevance" dimension. |
| Single source of truth deploys to both targets | No code forks. Changes go to source, then deploy via scp/cp. |

